he spine that help with posture. Often called a stability ball, these exercise techniques can improve balance, stability, and coordination.\r\n\r\nTo size a ball that fits your body, make sure your knees are at a right angle and your feet are flat on the floor. Simply sitting on the ball with proper posture will activate rarely used core muscles that are required to maintain good form. Frequent use of a stability ball has been shown to decrease discomfort to those who suffer from back pain. Try replacing your desk chair with an ab ball for portions of your day, or sit on one while watching TV.\r\n\r\nFor examples of core strengthening exercises on an fitness ball, view this <a href=\"http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?e=001aFzMCgwQ4dXxhKEJvy_LLmUHqMdpHlkQywowjfRL2Mfky_HSFbSqvaHDGaZOB7kY1JEPiODGq9ItohL5GHsst5PRslgJJS9GkwYRsC2rpPta4sPbvcj3lz8xQttsZN1vr3MBeqkz_VbeuCfjvD9--iEHbnV9taqQ\" shape=\"rect\" target=\"_blank\">slide-show from MayoClinic</a>.', 'Your Abs will Have a Ball!   ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'your-abs-will-have-a-ball', '', '', '2013-04-05 21:44:23', '2013-04-05 21:44:23', '', '0', 'http://www.sterling-wellness.com/?p=1623', '0', 'post', '', '0');
