ondiments.\n\nAlthough the US Food and Drug Administration has classified HFCS with the label \"generally recognized as safe,\" others argue that the ingredient is harmful to humans. Some researchers believe the inception of HFCS into the food supply has a direct correlation to the increase in obesity, type II diabetes, and metabolic syndrome. Furthermore, studies have found that HFCS can alter the appetite-regulating hormones Leptin and Ghrelin causing your brain and stomach to think you are still hungry even after a big meal.\n\nHigh Fructose Corn Syrup and table sugar both contain 4 calories per gram. Doctors and Dietitians agree that too much sugar in any form can be harmful. Since studies are still inconclusive about the direct effects of HFCS, limit processed foods that contain the sweetener and stick to fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean meats. Learn more about the controversy surrounding this ingredient from <a href=\"http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?e=001tCiLIb5gR23e6kby86Qr16Uau6EMz92t4sZ2_hP3n6YflL6RWEjr3af-Xhn1Bea1fRFq_wAVT4Z8wQCDgVoRD2JewsXlXcS896LdnEhTgMVWhDQ0h_l8ASkPR7g-FQ80H40MEZnmX8pVw_zC3-m4U63UZMS6AA2lCLrneGr1BnTSqn8Bx_bRBw==\" shape=\"rect\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> and the <a href=\"http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?e=001tCiLIb5gR225MRqfUn9WH5M45oU8OILU6inpyYKC_qK76wXRwbDinExH9a1i-difHwrXNHvSbv6s7OvMDHJpNVc8F3pkc8U8s2qjE8ywjQE_claZP8ZuKELnkzAqPLkh1R7EnS7VsVz0agUNgAXj9h1qXZury2swhq_Aamsm5Aw=\" shape=\"rect\" target=\"_blank\">Mayo Clinic</a>.', 'The Controversy Over Corn Syrup', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1662-revision', '', '', '2013-05-01 21:03:45', '2013-05-01 21:03:45', '', '1662', 'http://www.sterling-wellness.com/1662-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES('1664', '14', '2013-05-16 21:04:04', '2013-05-16 21:04:04', '[caption id=\"attachment_1665\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"150\"]<a href=\"http://www.sterling-wellness.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Marie-Beechy.jpg\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-1665\" title=\"Marie Beechy\" src=\"http://www.sterling-wellness.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Marie-Beechy-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a> Marie Beechy, RN, Primary Care Nurse[/caption]\r\n\r\nA: Workplace stress is a common occurrence. Most people today are trying to juggle having a family, building a career and maintaining some semblance of a personal life. These three tips will help you keep the stress from becoming unmanageable:\r\n<ol start=\"1\">\r\n	<li><strong>Deal with difficult situations ASAP-</strong> Avoiding a tough subject is one of the biggest causes of workplace stress. Don\'t wait until the boss approaches you about a problem. Take charge, and set the time and place to address it sooner rather than later. When you take control of a problem, it loses some of its stressful power over you.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Let go of some \'obligations\'-</strong> A lot of the stress we feel at work or home is a result of overbooking our lives. Learn to say no to things that aren\'t a top priority and focus on the things that are truly important.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Develop a mental list of coping skills-</strong> When the stress gets too high, stop and take action. Taking a 10 minute walk, calling a trusted friend, or practicing a mediation moment can make all the difference in reducing your stress.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nStress can build up quickly unless you make time to deal with it on a regular basis. For more ideas and techniques on dealing with stress, visit the <a href=\"http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?e=001tCiLIb5gR20UjJrwHZcACSXZWtf2TMt7eKf44eHDSZJW2EvL2DVGNDal5ZEpNwcylCYytsbJ5zsTrbuA39q81bbp7tsQkSFRXVOyKyCA0CJnESXDcGKFAl_MUrgaGVAlw15m_hmZd-sRf5Buzq-gBw==\" shape=\"rect\" target=\"_blank\">HelpGuide</a>.', 'Q: \"How do I deal with the stress I experience at work?\"', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'q-how-do-i-deal-with-the-stress-i-experience-at-work', '', '', '2013-05-01 21:05:50', '2013-05-01 21:05:50', '', '0', 'http://www.sterling-wellness.com/?p=1664', '0', 'post', '', '0');
