or hard surface. Because technical movements are more challenging in the sand, athletes develop quicker reflexes and expend more energy keeping a ball in play.\r\n\r\nIf you are new to this beach-style workout, start first on wet sand. Soft dry sand requires your stabilizer muscles to work harder. Much of your movement and power will be slowed with the resistance and challenge of sand. As with any outdoor activity, stay well hydrated, avoid peak hours of sun, and apply SPF 15 or higher. Stay aware of heat exhaustion symptoms for you and those around you. Visit Active.com to view <a href=\"http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?e=0016Gr8PS3I5r0gN2RDoDBsNVg6s0pI2FAGJDSF3-FTjeC721n6VoWQK7rRipwqf9_gymBJ-FT-AFhYGm1avOjtX3Y-h9kT17vl55Bu973g3fIuNLib3a9cUWiMFiibqNYqv2jUF6N_xmEAM02k0n3l-DSjWal1Rufy92btYmGCLuWPX3ZLi5mntivIskZlIoYy\" shape=\"rect\" target=\"_blank\">sand workouts and tips</a>.', 'Serving Up a Workout ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'serving-up-a-workout', '', '', '2013-07-03 16:25:54', '2013-07-03 16:25:54', '', '0', 'http://www.sterling-wellness.com/?p=1739', '0', 'post', '', '0');
