trong>Kosher Salt</strong> doesn\'t contain additives and is usually coarser than table salt. Kosher salt isn\'t recommended in recipes where it might not dissolve since it is a coarser grain.</li>\n	<li><strong>Table Salt</strong> is highly refined and has additives to prevent it from caking, making it free flowing. Table salt usually has iodine added and usually tastes more metallic because of the iodine. Table salt dissolves easily making it the best for cooking and baking.</li>\n	<li><strong>Sea Salt</strong> is made by dehydrating sea water from oceans or salt lakes and can vary widely in color and shape. Some contain impurities and minerals from the dehydrating process which often add flavor. Sea salts mimic the variety of salts in the body to some degree and contain trace minerals like magnesium, potassium, and calcium.</li>\n</ul>\nThe greater focus should be limiting the amount of sodium to 1,500-2,300mg no matter what type of salt you prefer. Those with high blood pressure or diabetes should aim for the lower end of that range. <a href=\"http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?f=001Ywe8N9ZzTwJwG0to7lzynpydEQt00js0Oa88RXahARubKFr932nyQ0zhfMMK1UI_9ORL3xkmSe2UKIZyYmPadneL1GlwiSX9RSftqGN1jxVV7FuF--IzGuGVK_OqPWXKvoEbXsonJZdeTYTAFASyi3mPxeaEL4CVkmfWg8H5gugpLLF8qQuVIP7QPxAWA3LkdAGCM-KbyOX6wTPVOT0OIfFTZwcHyONLsnSMFaBdfFxHNaSWq-5dyICqggcxLX2DQ5I9YS5iBxMuB3H7P_AAhIMYo-Hpqjsfh5m19VABhdQ=&amp;c=AeyPheMxmNwwU9wiONArMgcpmTzz69pVIwDHHMKlhLO3eOK0LxsRLw==&amp;ch=9VhzzZMODbeFIBBJg_2DGfFC6iGXIuQ--FP8cpzEO67TozoWNwN7BA==\" shape=\"rect\" target=\"_blank\"><em>More</em></a>', 'Shaking Up Different Types of Salt', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1995-revision', '', '', '2014-05-08 18:54:32', '2014-05-08 18:54:32', '', '1995', 'http://www.sterling-wellness.com/1995-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
