lood stream. Too little HDL can cause an imbalance in LDL, increasing the risk for heart disease. Although a portion of HDL levels are genetically determined, heart healthy choices can significantly impact your good cholesterol:</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Exercise</strong>- The best way to increase HDL is to exercise consistently.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Healthy Fats</strong>- Omega 3s found in salmon, flax seed, fish oil, olive oil, and avocados can increase HDL levels.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>If you smoke, quit-</strong> Tobacco smoke lowers HDL.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nA good HDL cholesterol level that provides protection against heart disease should be greater than 60mg/dL. Alternatively, an HDL result lower than 40mg/dL places you at higher risk for heart disease. <a href=\"http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?f=001Ywe8N9ZzTwJwG0to7lzynpydEQt00js0Oa88RXahARubKFr932nyQwtS9xLmjCE0xmFQ4oF0ymHzPNSA_20lIJTpHdh3NecllRlCAbD7w6tsAKbnxRQyRVQ17tKcoQ6uTz3uq4QHluqkX6RzJSPj-AB5YzlICrR3RDam0TfG6PXv3T6h-KgRVYmNJpuU44Ot5mBbcjrQH1c_yXXNLJqUrur01Z9gzq_fmMEj4VmCa9K9tLPog4Pc7l_n7N5zh4at&amp;c=AeyPheMxmNwwU9wiONArMgcpmTzz69pVIwDHHMKlhLO3eOK0LxsRLw==&amp;ch=9VhzzZMODbeFIBBJg_2DGfFC6iGXIuQ--FP8cpzEO67TozoWNwN7BA==\" shape=\"rect\" target=\"_blank\"><em>More</em></a>', 'Heart Healthy Choices for Better HDL', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1998-revision-2', '', '', '2014-05-08 18:56:32', '2014-05-08 18:56:32', '', '1998', 'http://www.sterling-wellness.com/1998-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES('2001', '14', '2014-05-21 18:56:46', '2014-05-21 18:56:46', 'How do you know if you are exercising at an intensity to reap the most benefit? A quick calculation of your heart rate during exercise will tell if you are hitting the target. If you don\'t have a heart rate monitor, follow this simple equation to determine your target heart rate:\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://ih.constantcontact.com/fs196/1103500019310/img/915.jpg\" alt=\"\" name=\"ACCOUNT.IMAGE.915\" width=\"100\" height=\"138\" align=\"left\" border=\"0\" hspace=\"5\" vspace=\"5\" />\r\n<h3 style=\"font-size: 14px; padding-left: 390px;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #339966;\"><strong>Maximum Heart Rate = 220-Age </strong></span></span></h3>\r\n<h3 style=\"font-size: 14px;\" align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #339966;\"><strong>Moderate Intensity: 50-70% of your maximum heart rate</strong></span></h3>\r\n<h3 style=\"font-size: 14px;\" align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #339966;\"><strong>Vigorous Intensity: 70-85% of your maximum heart rate</strong></span></h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo tell if you are hitting the target heart rate zone during exercise, take your pulse on your carotid artery (neck) or radial artery (wrist) for 30 seconds and multiply it by 2. This number indicates beats per minute, or BPM. If you can carry on a conversation during exercise, try increasing the intensity to a greater percentage of your maximum heart rate. Talk to your doctor if you are on certain medications including beta blockers which can lower your maximum and target heart rate. <a href=\"http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?f=001Ywe8N9ZzTwJwG0to7lzynpydEQt00js0Oa88RXahARubKFr932nyQwtS9xLmjCE0oQUexlqD_xynWxpCMWtpLdejgCif8gHw4ctK67zs6ks6djubGAiUkxgdkQfT_PtXxfD905EhLsqJdPrH0wVIPkzxNBbjQOtkKznvJ82ThXeo0PUcDQbHi8svxhQJM2NFaUYV7mRuaI0-pK4jMwBghNoa9Iin64Drhzx-o17wAflfLbvu5zDam8G99mt_xmz2prTxwtEp272zOjc-PgHQt1xeCOF7-Uif&amp;c=AeyPheMxmNwwU9wiONArMgcpmTzz69pVIwDHHMKlhLO3eOK0Lxs