ure is above 90º F. When in doubt, throw it out.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Always wear a life jacket</strong> when boating - no matter your age or swimming experience level. The U.S. Coast Guard estimates that life jackets could have saved the lives of more than 80% of boating fatality victims. Life jackets for adults do not work for children.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>The hours between 10 a.m. and 4 p.m.</strong> are the most hazardous for outdoor ultraviolet radiation exposure in the United States. Seek shade during these times. Remember to always reapply sunscreen with an SPF of 15 or higher every two hours when you\'re in the sun or right after you swim. Make sure the sunscreen protects against both UVA and UVB rays.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Watch for signs of heat exhaustion or heat stroke</strong>, especially in children. Kids\' bodies absorb more heat on a hot day than adults do. Also, children are less able to lower their body heat by sweating. A child\'s body temperature may increase three to five times as fast as an adult\'s body temperature. Signs of trouble include red and hot skin, absence of sweating, an abnormally fast or slow pulse, a throbbing headache, dizziness, confusion, or acting strangely. <a href=\"http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?f=001VOpxTRrKs6wv0vEMJeDCao1vG6r3CubnDbE3xY3TTeaE6PAdxEPxNbimSTc8qmUclO-FPxCuIc0Ue07FMb31SRQKF2SAAwmTErNTBlLCfQMjD89d3H97HQuNBYiLSNDK2PukZOj7Y2G3OD1sGHll11CPcMFQVoCnqzUX2qOthtbp_EumQGvxNpFMl9n5NnbPI6ff-IbnRGT8BZAIscAgIlm68HTj_j2PXwSakk3ivUcbzPHFUZoVeg==&amp;c=n0lHuwNSFUvafKGWQk6bg7qT_vcINbxG2MABEU1kGiPWPF78mny1fw==&amp;ch=carGuHigQ4jT9_8Vn1-PB8e7i0BmDi-fe9TxToN09rBWiaklVupmYA==\" shape=\"rect\" target=\"_blank\"><em>More</em></a>', 'Prevent Summer Emergencies', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'prevent-summer-emergencies', '', '', '2014-07-09 19:29:26', '2014-07-09 19:29:26', '', '0', 'http://www.sterling-wellness.com/?p=2048', '0', 'post', '', '0');
