is critical in improving the odds of survival. The most common sign of a heart attack in both men and women is chest pain or discomfort that comes on quickly, goes away, and then comes back. Although both genders experience similar warning signs, there are often slight differences in the signs of a heart attack between men and women:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Women </strong>may show less obvious symptoms and are more likely to have shortness of breath, nausea, and vomiting. Women may experience unusual tiredness for days, and pain in the back, shoulders, or jaw.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Men</strong> are more likely to experience upper body discomfort in one or both arms, shortness of breath and the hallmark chest pain.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nBeing aware of the different possible symptoms of a heart attack is equally important in both genders for prompt medical intervention. If you think you or someone around you is experiencing a heart attack, your first step should be to contact 911. Simply providing chest compressions to someone in cardiac arrest is a safe and effective way for a bystander to provide life-saving techniques. <a href=\"http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?f=0017mQ0Vc9mTDayFEc5IUUHkUY6YeDaODTbYps_BuCFoJMOHhp6JwtqYr2oaer1evNuE8ipgbvJ7aTQZKoaUjRjLqy9XwSq5tefODgO20IkSy2oFtIP2pCm-dN9fZyJEGVCN05UTgF0D5rlF7xYqFa1yUrk-Mh5sGVDA8PpUvL28mXAOCaaMM1o-rGIffshzKwPbozJs65gzJw8xnngYPIAbQbwiH2Q3cxzRF3t7imRaxxlSHa06OvGUN26DxsqAKoz-sk0gRqGqnDHt0kNNBPUJQ==&amp;c=7kuIi6nbcTS4KiiKEBSTgbdPa3ftbimuf4k16i1FNU9V3ULGVwbfYQ==&amp;ch=ozkcvucfpT9MG5m3KdXxOTGo7_ZcgY8FarDYLgtYwrTS_vtQouxHVQ==\" shape=\"rect\" target=\"_blank\"><em>More</em></a>', 'Heart Attack Symptoms by Gender', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'heart-attack-symptoms-by-gender', '', '', '2015-02-26 20:31:40', '2015-02-26 20:31:40', '', '0', 'http://www.sterling-wellness.com/?p=2188', '0', 'post', '', '0');
