INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES('2222', '14', '2015-03-16 11:19:11', '2015-03-16 17:19:11', '<a href=\"http://www.sterling-wellness.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Chicken.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-2219\" src=\"http://www.sterling-wellness.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Chicken-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Chicken\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>For the casual consumer, all eggs can be a healthy part of any diet thanks to their high-quality protein, 13 essential vitamins and minerals, and low calorie density at just 70 calories per egg. However, consumers are still left with mind-boggling choices based on the source, farming practices, and nutrition of eggs:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Brown eggs</strong> are nearly identical in nutritional value as white eggs even though the brown variety are often marketed as being healthier. The color of the eggshell is determined solely by the color of the hen laying the egg.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Organic eggs</strong> come from antibiotic-free and hormone-free chickens that eat only organic grain grown on land free from pesticides and fertilizers for at least 3 years.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Free-Range eggs</strong> come from chickens that are allowed to roam freely outdoors. Studies have found pastured hens have higher levels of omega 3s and vitamins A and E.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Cage-Free</strong> hens may still be confined to close quarters with other hens, just not in cages.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>The size difference</strong> between medium, large, extra-large, or jumbo eggs come from the genetic breed of then hen and are affected by the bird\'s feed intake and farming techniques.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Grade AA</strong> eggs are the highest quality available, followed by Grade A then B, respectively.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAlthough 100% of the cholesterol in an egg is found in the yolk, the yellow center also contains most of the calcium, iron, zinc, choline and vitamins A, D, E, and K. Those concerned with their cholesterol levels may consider alternating with egg whites, cholesterol free egg substitutes, or limiting other sources of cholesterol throughout the day. <a href=\"http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?f=001GHD60b0JLJrECcZUd6Uqyh_NkVZcld0iLkECO6b2h-ai5AkK4B0uUJmZuNka4P7aDSg6fUONU7v1-AV0owMAnqurl7ilEMmtCLbSUtTCYWTchlYEbnEbL_VGNA1HGLsWNgLPbCDFfJaMwRNl8BcZ7p_DXGFMNS0MJJx1LMLCx_zDXZHb7JH91u1YMFkSnPBw2WUC6uutz11d3WHtptnMoq4gH0tDTlqlY1nzB7l7wOw=&amp;c=6gutJPHZfMCRd0c6TfecsBIsnNxQDcLxVJd2uvxJlkoVXjJ6I-0k9g==&amp;ch=YCvv2OQhHU2nCD5xNj8fkRSXZ0UcqdWXZu3gDzDUB1x3Yh-jMVVC7A==\"><em>More</em></a>', 'Unscrambling the Differences Between Eggs', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'unscrambling-the-differences-between-eggs', '', '', '2015-03-20 11:20:09', '2015-03-20 17:20:09', '', '0', 'http://www.sterling-wellness.com/?p=2222', '0', 'post', '', '0');
