INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES('2240', '14', '2015-04-05 11:09:45', '2015-04-05 17:09:45', '<div><img src=\"http://ih.constantcontact.com/fs041/1103500019310/img/158.jpg?a=1120545671013\" alt=\"\" width=\"165\" height=\"95\" name=\"ACCOUNT.IMAGE.158\" align=\"right\" border=\"0\" hspace=\"5\" vspace=\"5\" />Nearly one third of those who have high blood pressure, or hypertension, aren\'t aware of it.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nDespite uncontrollable risk factors such as age and family history, there are many factors in the treatment and management of your blood pressure that you can control.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Lifestyle Change-</strong> Maintain a healthy weight, exercise regularly, eat a heart healthy diet that limits salt, and manage stress.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Self-Monitoring</strong>- Home monitoring provides a complete picture of how well blood pressure is being controlled. Have your doctor check that your cuff fits properly. Sit with arm supported at heart level and measure your blood pressure at the same time each day.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Prescription Compliance</strong>- Your doctor may adjust the type of medication and dosage if you experience negative side effects. Do not stop taking prescription blood pressure medicine without first talking to your doctor about side effects and other options.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf left untreated for long periods of time, hypertension can lead to heart disease, an increased risk for stroke, and even kidney failure. A normal blood pressure reading is &lt;120/80 mm/Hg. Hypertension occurs at a blood pressure level over 140/90 mm/Hg. <a href=\"http://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/health-topics/topics/hbp\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\" shape=\"rect\">More</a>\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Self-Care for High Blood Pressure', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'self-care-for-high-blood-pressure', '', '', '2015-04-23 11:11:06', '2015-04-23 17:11:06', '', '0', 'http://www.sterling-wellness.com/?p=2240', '0', 'post', '', '0');
