INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES('2259', '14', '2015-05-05 14:23:44', '2015-05-05 20:23:44', '<div>The brain and digestive system share a complex connection that becomes more vulnerable during times of stress. The gut is also known as the second brain and may explain how stress affects a wide range of digestive issues including:<a href=\"http://www.sterling-wellness.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Stomach.png\"><img class=\"alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-2262\" src=\"http://www.sterling-wellness.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Stomach-150x150.png\" alt=\"Stomach\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Irritable Bowel Syndrome</li>\r\n	<li>Ulcers</li>\r\n	<li>Heart burn and indigestion</li>\r\n	<li>Inflammatory Bowel Diseases</li>\r\n	<li>Changes in appetite</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHaving a gut-feeling is one indication of how strong the brain and digestive tract communicate during times of stress. When stress occurs, the brain sends signals to the digestive system to either slow digestion or stop it completely so all energy is being diverted to the stressor. Long term stress, when left unmanaged, leads to a host of gastrointestional disorders and explains why inflammatory bowel diseases like Chron\'s and colitis are exacerbated during times of chronic stress.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div>If you think stress may be the root of your digestive issues, stress management techniques, cognitive behavior therapy, relaxation therapy, and hypnosis have all been proven effective therapies to provide relief.<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/parenting/features/anxiety-stress-and-stomachaches\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\" shape=\"rect\">More</a></div>', 'Stress and Your Stomach', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'stress-and-your-stomach', '', '', '2015-05-21 14:29:28', '2015-05-21 20:29:28', '', '0', 'http://www.sterling-wellness.com/?p=2259', '0', 'post', '', '0');
